{
  "doc_id": "22293",
  "text": "A number of informative studies by Lieber et al. (reviewed in [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ) have provided evidence that dilinoleoylphosphatidylcholine (DLPC), the major phospholipid species (43-50%) in polyenylphosphatidylcholine (PPC) extracted from soybeans, is able to protect against liver damage associated with excessive alcohol intake. In vitro, DLPC has a number of hepatoprotective properties including the ability to reduce alcohol-induced hepatocyte apoptosis, cytochrome P450IIE1 (CYP2E1) induction, mitochondrial respiratory dysfunction, and TNF-a generation by Kupffer cells. In addition to reducing lipid peroxidation and oxidative stress, DLPC inhibits hepatic fibrosis, by affecting hepatic stellate cell proliferation and collagen accumulation [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Soybean PPC also reduces hyperlipidemia and fatty liver in rats given excess alcohol, an effect associated with improved hepatic fatty acid oxidation [CITATION_5] .",
